There are a lot of similar names in the skill column, which makes the analysis difficult. I can think of two ways to deal with the messy skill counts:

  1. use word counts to find the most frequent words
  2. use clustering technique to group similar words together
  3. use fuzzwuzzy library to fuzzy match similar words

1. word counts¶

In [17]:
# join all words together
all_text = ' '.join(exploded_df['cleaned_required_skills'].dropna().astype(str))
# Split the text into individual words and count occurrences
word_counts = Counter(all_text.split())
# convert to a dataframe
word_count_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(word_counts, orient='index', columns=['count']).reset_index()
word_count_df.rename(columns={'index': 'word'}, inplace=True)

# Sort the DataFrame by count in descending order
word_count_df = word_count_df.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

Out[29]:
1735

Problems:

  1. Some skills 'r' and 'c++' is in a lot of clusters due to its simple form. 'r' only has 167 instances in the data, but got 2659 in the total count when use it as the most frequent word.
  2. Some skills have the 'skill' or 'skills' in their string which is unnecessry.
  3. Some clusters have many different skills, so that the most frequent word can not represent the cluster.

Attempted solutions:

  1. add context specific qualifiers to the words, like 'r language' and 'c++ language'.
  2. tune the number of clusters, there is a trade off here: high number of clusters can have clusters with less different words in them but some similar words may get into different clusters. low number of clusters are vice versa.
  3. add a threshold to the percentage of most frequent word in the cluster, for instance, if the most frequent word is less than 50% of the cluster, this cluster is excluded from the calculation.

Overall, they looks very similar, the most common skills are:

sql, python, communication, data visualization, machine learning, statistic, r, data modeling, excel, power bi, tableau, problem solving, programming, data science

In two visuals: project management (~clustering), collaboration/data mining (~fuzzy match), analytical (~word count)

In only one visual: cloud (word count), reporting (clustering)

Conclusiong:

  1. Word count needs the most human input and preprocessing.
  2. K-means clustering is code intensive, need the most computation power and also need some human input to make it work properly.
  3. Fuzzy match is the best performing of all three techniques. Needs minimum human input and generate decent report with little coding.
  4. Eventough Fuzzy match is the best of all three, the best practice is still make multiple approach so I can have more confidence that the algorithm generate reliable result.
  5. This part is the most challenging, yet most fruitful. It proves utilizing AI, machine learning and NLP can quickly extract information from complex dataset. Utilizing these tools can save a lot of time when analyzing the job market and searching jobs.
